TO BE ENTITLED
HB161 INTRODUCED
29 AN ACT
30
31 Relating to consumer protection; to require an app
32 store provider to take certain actions regarding age
33 verification, parental notification, and data protection; to
34 prohibit an app store provider or developer from taking
35 certain actions that allow minors to access apps without
36 parental consent; to require the Attorney General to adopt
37 rules; and to authorize the Attorney General to bring an
38 action for a violation as a deceptive trade practice.
39 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
40 Section 1. For the purposes of this act, the following
41 terms have the following meanings:
42 (1) ACCOUNT HOLDER. The individual associated with a
43 mobile device.
44 (2) AGE CATEGORY. Whether an individual is: (i) under
45 13 years of age; (ii) at least 13 years of age but less than
46 16 years of age; (iii) at least 16 years of age but less than
47 18 years of age; or (iv) at least 18 years of age.
48 (3) AGE CATEGORY DATA. Information about a user's age
49 category which is collected by an app store developer and
50 shared with a developer.
51 (4) AGE RATING. A classification that assesses the
52 suitability of an app's content and functions for different
53 age groups.
54 (5) APP. A software application or electronic service
55 that a user may run or direct on a mobile device. The term
56 includes pre-installed apps.
Page 2

includes pre-installed apps.
HB161 INTRODUCED
57 (6) APP STORE. A publicly available website, software
58 application, or electronic service that allows account holders
59 to download apps from third-party developers onto a mobile
60 device.
61 (7) APP STORE PROVIDER. An entity that owns, operates,
62 or controls an app store that allows account holders in the
63 state to download apps onto a mobile device.
64 (8) CONTENT DESCRIPTION. A description of the specific
65 content elements or functions that inform an app's age rating.
66 (9) DEVELOPER. An entity that owns or controls an app
67 made available through an app store or a pre-installed app.
68 (10) MINOR. An individual under 18 years of age, unless
69 the individual is married or legally emancipated.
70 (11) MINOR ACCOUNT. An account with an app store
71 provider that is established by an individual who the app
72 store provider has determined is a minor.
73 (12) MOBILE DEVICE. A phone or general-purpose tablet
74 that: (i) provides cellular or wireless connectivity; (ii) is
75 capable of connecting to the Internet; (iii) runs a mobile
76 operating system; and (iv) is capable of running apps through
77 the mobile operating system.
78 (13) MOBILE OPERATING SYSTEM. Software that: (i)
79 manages mobile device hardware resources; (ii) provides common
80 services for mobile device programs; (iii) controls memory
81 allocation; and (iv) provides interfaces for apps to access
82 device functionality.
83 (14) PARENT. With respect to a minor, any of the
84 following individuals:
Page 3

following individuals:
HB161 INTRODUCED
85 a. A biological parent.
86 b. A legal guardian.
87 c. An individual with legal custody.
88 (15) PARENT ACCOUNT. An account with an app store
89 provider which is affiliated with one or more minor accounts
90 and which is verified to have been established by an
91 individual who the app store provider has determined is not a
92 minor.
93 (16) PARENTAL CONSENT DISCLOSURE. The following
94 information that an app store provider is required to provide
95 to a parent before obtaining parental disclosure:
96 a. A description of the personal data collected by the
97 app from a user.
98 b. A description of the personal data shared by the app
99 with any third party.
100 c. Any methods implemented by the developer to protect
101 personal data.
102 d. The age rating of the app or in-app purchase, if
103 available.
104 e. The content description of the app or in-app
105 purchase, if available.
106 (17) PRE-INSTALLED APP. Any app, or portion of an app,
107 that is present on a mobile device at the time of purchase,
108 initial activation, or first use by the consumer. The term
109 includes, but is not limited to: (i) browsers; (ii) search
110 engines; (iii) messaging apps; and (iv) other apps, or
111 portions of apps, that are installed or partially installed by
112 the device manufacturer, wireless services provider, retailer,
Page 4

the device manufacturer, wireless services provider, retailer,
HB161 INTRODUCED
113 or any other party prior to the purchase, initial activation,
114 or first use of the device by the customer and that may be
115 updated thereafter. The term does not include: (i) core
116 operating system functions; (ii) essential device drivers; and
117 (iii) applications necessary for basic device operation such
118 as phone and settings applications.
119 (18) SIGNIFICANT CHANGE. A material modification to an
120 app's terms of service or privacy policy which does any of the
121 following:
122 a. Changes the categories of data collected, stored, or
123 shared.
124 b. Adds new monetization features, including, but not
125 limited to, in-app purchases or advertisements, where no such
126 features were previously present.
127 c. Alters the app's age rating or content descriptions.
128 (19) VERIFIABLE PARENTAL CONSENT. Authorization that
129 meets all of the following criteria:
130 a. Is provided by an individual who the app store
131 provider has verified is at least 18 years of age.
132 b. Is given after the app store provider has clearly
133 and conspicuously provided the parental consent disclosure to
134 the individual.
135 c. Requires the parent to make an affirmative choice to
136 either grant consent or decline consent.
137 Section 2. (a) An app store provider shall do both of
138 the following when an individual located in this state creates
139 an account with the app store provider, or before October 1,
140 2027, for all accounts in existence on October 2, 2026:
Page 5

2027, for all accounts in existence on October 2, 2026:
HB161 INTRODUCED
141 (1) Request age category information from the
142 individual.
143 (2) Verify the individual's age category using one of
144 the following:
145 a. Commercially available methods that are reasonably
146 designed to ensure accuracy.
147 b. An age verification system that complies with rules
148 adopted pursuant to this act.
149 (b) For the purposes of this section, a method is
150 commercially available if the method includes both: (i)
151 affirmative age attestation by an individual who is reasonably
152 believed to be the parent or legal guardian of the minor; and
153 (ii) other information collected in the ordinary course of
154 account creation or use.
155 Section 3. An app store provider shall do all of the
156 following when an individual is determined to be a minor
157 pursuant to Section 1:
158 (1) Require the account to be affiliated with a parent
159 account.
160 (2) Obtain verifiable parental consent from the holder
161 of the affiliated parent account before allowing the minor to:
162 (i) download an app; (ii) purchase an app; or (iii) make an
163 in-app purchase.
164 (3) Provide a mechanism for the holder of the
165 affiliated parent account to withdraw consent and notify
166 developers when the holder of a parent account withdraws
167 consent.
168 Section 4. An app store provider shall do both of the
Page 6

Section 4. An app store provider shall do both of the
HB161 INTRODUCED
169 following after receiving notice of a significant change from
170 a developer:
171 (1) Notify the user of the significant change.
172 (2) For a minor account, do both of the following:
173 a. Notify the holder of the affiliated parent account.
174 b. Obtain renewed verifiable parental consent before
175 providing access to the significantly changed version of the
176 app.
177 Section 5. An app store provider shall provide
178 developers with real-time access to both of the following:
179 (1) Age category data for each user located in this
180 state.
181 (2) The status of verifiable parental consent for each
182 minor located in this state.
183 Section 6. An app store provider shall protect personal
184 age verification data by doing both of the following:
185 (1) Limiting the collection and processing to data
186 necessary to: (i) verify a user's age; (ii) obtain parental
187 consent; or (iii) maintain compliance records.
188 (2) Transmitting personal age verification data using
189 industry-standard encryption protocols that ensure data
190 integrity and data confidentiality.
191 Section 7. An app store provider shall do both of the
192 following with respect to pre-installed apps:
193 (1) Provide available age category information in
194 response to a request from a developer.
195 (2) Take reasonable measures to facilitate verifiable
196 parental consent for use of a pre-installed app in response to
Page 7

parental consent for use of a pre-installed app in response to
HB161 INTRODUCED
197 a request from a developer.
198 Section 8. An app store provider may not do any of the
199 following:
200 (1) Enforce a contract or terms of service against a
201 minor unless the app store provider has obtained verifiable
202 parental consent.
203 (2) Knowingly misrepresent the information in the
204 parental consent disclosure.
205 (3) Share age category data or any other associated
206 data except as required by law or as required by this act
207 between an app store provider and a developer.
208 Section 9. (a) A developer shall do all of the
209 following:
210 (1) Verify through the app store's data sharing
211 methods: (i) the age category of users located in this state;
212 and (ii) for a minor account, whether verifiable parental
213 consent has been obtained.
214 (2) Notify app store providers of any significant
215 change to an app.
216 (3) Limit use of age category data received from an app
217 store provider to: (i) enforce developer-created age-related
218 restrictions, protections, or defaults; (ii) ensure compliance
219 with applicable laws or regulations; or (iii) implement
220 safety-related features or defaults.
221 (4) Request age category data or verifiable parental
222 consent in all of the following scenarios:
223 a. Whenever an account holder does any of the
224 following:
Page 8

following:
HB161 INTRODUCED
225 1. Downloads an app.
226 2. Purchases an app.
227 3. Launches a pre-installed app for the first time.
228 b. When implementing a significant change to an app.
229 c. To comply with applicable law.
230 (5) When implementing any developer-created age-related
231 restrictions, safety-related features, or defaults, use the
232 lowest age category indicated by either: (i) age category data
233 received through the app store's data sharing methods; or (ii)
234 age data independently collected by the developer.
235 (b) A developer may request age category data in any of
236 the following scenarios:
237 (1) No more than once during each 12-month period to
238 verify either of the following:
239 a. The accuracy of age category data associated with an
240 account holder.
241 b. Continued account use within the age category.
242 (2) When there is reasonable suspicion of either of the
243 following:
244 a. Account transfer.
245 b. Misuse outside of the age category.
246 (3) At the time an account holder creates a new account
247 with the developer.
248 (c) A developer may not do any of the following:
249 (1) Enforce a contract or terms of service against a
250 minor unless the developer has verified through the app store
251 provider that verifiable parental consent has been obtained.
252 (2) Knowingly misrepresent any information in the
Page 9

(2) Knowingly misrepresent any information in the
