253 parental consent disclosure.
254 (3) Share age category data with any person.
255 Section 10. The Attorney General shall adopt rules
256 establishing processes and means by which an app store
257 provider may verify whether an account holder is a minor in
258 accordance with this act.
259 Section 11. (a) Any knowing or reckless violation of
260 this act is deemed a deceptive trade practice actionable under
261 Chapter 19 of Title 8 of the Code of Alabama 1975. If the
262 Attorney General has reason to believe that an entity is in
263 violation of this act, the Attorney General may bring an
264 action against the entity for an unfair or deceptive trade
265 practice. In addition to other remedies available under
266 Chapter 19 of Title 8 of the Code of Alabama 1975, the
267 Attorney General may collect a civil penalty of up to seven
268 thousand five hundred dollars ($7,500) per violation,
269 reasonable attorney fees, and court costs.
270 (b) If a violation described in subsection (a) is part
271 of a consistent pattern of knowing or reckless conduct, the
272 Attorney General may seek punitive damages against the entity.
273 (c) An action for a claim under this section must be
274 brought within one year from the date the Attorney General
275 knew or reasonably should have known of the alleged violation.
276 (d) This section does not preclude any other available
277 remedy at law or equity.
278 Section 12. (a) A developer is not liable for a
279 violation of this act if the developer demonstrates all of the
280 following:
Page 10

following:
HB161 INTRODUCED
281 (1) The developer relied in good faith on applicable
282 age category data received through an app store's data sharing
283 methods.
284 (2) The developer relied in good faith on notification
285 from an app store provider that verifiable parental consent
286 was obtained.
287 (3) The developer complied with the requirements of
288 this act.
289 (b) A developer is not liable for a violation of
290 Section 9(c)(2) if the developer: (i) uses widely adopted
291 industry standards to determine the app's age category and
292 content description; and (ii) applies those standards
293 consistently and in good faith.
294 (c) Notwithstanding subsection (a), the safe harbor
295 provision applies only to actions brought under this act and
296 does not limit a developer or app store provider's liability
297 under any other applicable law.
298 Section 13. Nothing in this act shall be construed to
299 do any of the following:
300 (1) Prevent an app store provider or developer from
301 taking reasonable measures to do any of the following:
302 a. Block, detect, or prevent distribution to minors of:
303 (i) unlawful material; (ii) obscene material; or (iii) other
304 harmful material.
305 b. Block or filter spam.
306 c. Prevent criminal activity.
307 d. Protect app store or app security.
308 (2) Require an app store provider or developer to
Page 11

(2) Require an app store provider or developer to
HB161 INTRODUCED
309 disclose user information to a developer beyond age category
310 or verification of parental consent status.
311 (3) Allow an app store provider or developer to
312 implement measures required by this act in a manner that is:
313 (i) arbitrary; (ii) capricious; (iii) anticompetitive; or (iv)
314 unlawful.
315 (4) Require a developer to collect, retain, reidentify,
316 or link any information beyond what is both:
317 a. Necessary to verify age category data as required by
318 this act; and
319 b. Collected, retained, reidentified, or linked in the
320 developer's ordinary course of business.
321 (5) Require an app store provider or developer to block
322 access to an application that an account holder has downloaded
323 or installed onto a mobile device prior to October 1, 2026,
324 except to the extent that either:
325 a. A parent account revokes verifiable consent for an
326 affiliated minor account; or
327 b. There has been a significant change to the
328 application.
329 Section 14. This act shall become effective on October
330 1, 2026.
